{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499420","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499420"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:59:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:59:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1496"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1496"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.38,0.02,0.05,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109477"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1496"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1496"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91844"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45787"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109477"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old man presents with a complaint of numbness in his left big toe. He has just returned from a five day mountain trek where the temperatures did not get much above -10\u00b0C. He is normally in good health, drinks about four glasses of wine at weekends and has a five pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E The skin over his toe looks pale and waxy. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A rewarming process of the toe is started, and this brings on severe pain and tenderness over the nail (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate action for relief of his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["NSAIDs","Nail decompression","Amputation","Local ice pack","Keep rewarming"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with a frostbite injury of his big toe because of the presence of numbness, heaviness and pale discolouration of the toe after walking in very cold weather for a prolonged period. The patient is also a smoker, which is a risk factor for frostbite injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe best initial step of management of frost bite is to start rewarming the affected site to restore blood flow and reduce the tissue damage that is continuously going on. Rewarming is associated with severe pain due to various reasons like the release of cytokines and reperfusion injury which - as in this case - can lead to a localised collection of fluid under the skin in a fixed space. This is a version of the compartment syndrome. The best step to relieve the pain in these circumstances is to perform \u003Cstrong\u003Enail decompression\u003C/strong\u003E which leads to leakage of fluid and relieving of pain due to decreased pressure. This can be done by making a hole in the overlying nail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENSAIDs\u003C/strong\u003E can be employed in the treatment along with decompression, but they are usually not strong enough to decrease the pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAmputation\u003C/strong\u003E of the toe is an extreme measure and it is usually not performed for pain relief even when it is done, it is delayed till 60-90 days after the injury because of the good prognosis of the disease due to prompt management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocal ice packs \u003C/strong\u003Eare usually used to alleviate pain in general settings but the only thing this will do is increase the damage because the primary injury is caused because of low temperature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERewarming\u003C/strong\u003E the affected area again would not be appropriate because it will lead to more collection of fluid and the pain in the toe will keep increasing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrostbite has a prejudice for distal extremities, digits, and those portions of exposed skin with decreased perfusion (nose, ears) and less insulation. As the temperature of exposed skin drops, endothelial cell damage can cause localised oedema in the extremity. Hyperviscous intravascular flow and vasodilation cause slowing forces, resulting in microthrombi. The constellation of microvascular injury, venous stasis, and microthrombi all contribute to the development of ischaemia attributed to frostbite.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The best initial acute step for pain management in frostbite is rewarming","Complications of rewarming include severe pain, blister formation and tissue necrosis"],"references":["Zaramo T Z, Green JK, Janis JE. Practical Review of the Current Management of Frostbite Injuries. Plast Reconstr Surg Glob Open 2022;10:e4618;","Sheridan RL, Goverman JM, Walker TG.  Diagnosis and Treatment of Frostbite. N Engl J Med 2022;386:2213-20."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91844"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1496"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18063"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18063","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18063"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1a800ef2-9546-4467-98bc-02d0d4c45bef.jpg","thumbUrl":"h